  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve expensive wine at Thanksgiving or save money for everyday bottles?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Thanksgiving is perfect for mid-range wines ($15-30) that offer complexity without breaking the bank, since rich holiday foods can overwhelm subtle nuances in expensive bottles. Focus on food-friendly varietals like Côtes du Rhône, Oregon Pinot Noir, or Finger Lakes Riesling that enhance the meal rather than competing with it. Save your premium bottles for quieter dinners where guests can truly appreciate their subtleties.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest wine mistake people make at Thanksgiving?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is serving wines that are too heavy or tannic, like big Cabernets or oaked Chardonnays, which clash with Thanksgiving's herb-forward dishes and sweet elements. These powerful wines overwhelm delicate turkey flavors and create unpleasant interactions with cranberry sauce's tartness. Instead, choose wines with bright acidity and moderate alcohol that complement rather than compete with your carefully prepared feast.</p>
